    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2612808983" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2612808983" />
    <a title="Julie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3292905-julie"><img alt="Julie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1508646859p2/3292905.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2612808983?book_show_action=true">Jan 03, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Julie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Julie" href="/user/show/3292905-julie">Julie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9780736683005" href="/book/show/7630066-ghost-soldiers">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3292905-julie?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2612808983" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12686032783211382624">Lieutenant Colonel Henry Andrew Mucci the commanding officer of a battalion of Army Rangers was chosen to lead the rescue mission to liberate Allied POWs from Cabantuan prison camp, which was used by the Japanese after they invaded the Philippines. <br/><br/>Mucci is described as having “a colorful forceful personality.&quot; Indeed, “Henry Andrew Mucci was such a lavish and convincing persuader that the Rangers supplied him with another nickname, HAM.” He was the sort of leader people will follow to the ends </span>
  <span id="freeText12686032783211382624" style="display:none">Lieutenant Colonel Henry Andrew Mucci the commanding officer of a battalion of Army Rangers was chosen to lead the rescue mission to liberate Allied POWs from Cabantuan prison camp, which was used by the Japanese after they invaded the Philippines. <br /><br />Mucci is described as having “a colorful forceful personality." Indeed, “Henry Andrew Mucci was such a lavish and convincing persuader that the Rangers supplied him with another nickname, HAM.” He was the sort of leader people will follow to the ends of the earth. “His men adored him in large part because anything he asked them to do and anywhere he asked them to go, he was right there alongside them.” He made the men believe they could do anything. As he talked to his Rangers about the rescue mission, he asked them to “Swear that you’ll die fighting rather than let any harm come to those prisoners.”<br /><br />Mucci selected Captain Robert Prince, as Assault Commander. His job was to design the master plan for the raid on the prison stockade. “Prince possessed the quiet optimism of a forward thinker. Someone with a prudent understated judgement about people and situations. Prince was blessed with the rarest of gifts, steady nerves. He had the take it or leave it equanimity of a citizen soldier.”<br /><br />Doctor Ralph Emerson Hibbs is described as “A slender bespectacled man with some of the bearing and affable features of the young Jimmy Stewart, Hibbs kept his sense of humor no matter how grim things got. His eyes always lit with the suggestion of mischief.” Hibbs was responsible for the care of 700 soldiers. They were so exhausted, as one soldier put it that “even our hair was tired.” Indeed, they were fighting with improvised weapons, living on improvised food.” They felt they had been abandoned. <br /><br />Cabanatuan Prison Camp had housed around 8,000 Americans. However, able bodied prisoners were sent to Japan to provide labor in industries such as coal mining, or work as stevedores loading and unloading cargo ships. “Now all that was left at Cabanatuan were the dregs. The sickest and the weakest. The ‘Ghosts of Bataan’ they called themselves with a mixture of black humor and the peculiar proud toughness of the orphaned.” <br /><br />The prisoners are described as being "accustomed to the art of scraping by. The majority of them had grown up on small farms and ranches during the depths of the Great Depression. They knew discipline and self-reliance […] They understood how to scrimp and barter and improvise.” <br /><br />To keep their spirits up, Lieutenant Henry Lee wrote and recited poetry to his fellow soldiers. He was held in high esteem and known as the “poet of Bataan.” <br /><br />To survive in Cabanatuan, they had to learn to be cunning and seize opportunities wherever they could. An underground network developed through some outside people located in Manila who wanted to help the prisoners any way they could. They helped to smuggle in food and other resources. One such helper was an ecclesiastical Catholic priest, Father Heinz Buttenbruck who "was said to have a photographic memory and he brought in and out scores of personal messages during his weekly visits. Messages that proved invaluable to the workings of the underground.”<br /><br />Finally, when the Rangers arrived at Cabanatuan, they were appalled at the condition of the prisoners they were liberating and described them as, “sickly old birds that had been plucked” and “old beyond years” and “so far down the starvation trail.” They were so frail that “by the dozens and scores they would have to be carried or at the very least escorted arm in arm.” Some had to be led by the hand.<br /><br />Later, after the prison camp had been evacuated, a group of soldiers and a photographer returned to the camp to find vital documents, such as “death logs, cemetery layouts and medical records” the prisoners had kept safely hidden. “Buried beneath the shack that used to be the library they found a cache of camp literature including prison diaries, sketch books and the poems of Henry Lee.” The following is one of Lieutenant Henry Lee’s poems:<br /><br />“Westward we came across the smiling waves,<br />West to the outpost of our country’s might<br />“Romantic land of brilliant tropic light”<br />Our land of broken memories and graves<br /><br />Eastward we go and home, so few<br />Wrapped in their beds of clay our comrades sleep<br />The memories of this land are branded deep<br />And lost is the youth we knew.”<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12686032783211382624" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


